
                              ~CY* ~CWcolour ~CY*

~CYCommand: ~CWcolour
~CYUsage  : ~CWcolour

~CWThis command toggles colour on and off. The colour itself is
~CWcontrolled by embedded tags in text strings which all begin 
~CWwith a '~', eg ^~FG.

~CWThey are the following...

~CWControl tags...

^~RS : Rest terminal to default state
^~RV : ~RVReverse video               ~RS
^~OL : ~OLBold
^~LI : ~LIBlink/flash text.~RS This only works on some terminals, others may
      simply display it as bold.
^~UL : ~ULUnderline text.~RS As with blink this doesn't work on all terminals,
      some just display it as bold.

~CWForeground colour tags...

^~FK : Foreground black
^~FM : ~FMMagenta/purple
^~FR : ~FRRed
^~FY : ~FYYellow/orange
^~FG : ~FGGreen
^~FB : ~FBBlue
^~FT : ~FTTurquoise/bright blue
^~FW : ~FWWhite
^~CK : ~CKForeground black
^~CM : ~CMMagenta/purple
^~CR : ~CRRed
^~CY : ~CYYellow/orange
^~CG : ~CGGreen
^~CB : ~CBBlue
^~CT : ~CTTurquoise/bright blue
^~CW : ~CWWhite

Background colour tags...

^~BK : ~BKBackground black      ~RS
^~BM : ~BMMagenta/purple        ~RS
^~BR : ~BRRed                   ~RS
^~BY : ~BYYellow/orange         ~RS
^~BG : ~BGGreen                 ~RS
^~BB : ~BBBlue                  ~RS
^~BT : ~BTTurquoise/bright blue ~RS
^~BW : ~CK~BWWhite                 ~RS

So this: "^~FG^~BBhello world" would produce ~FG~BBhello world~RS

To display the colour tags as themselves without them producing a colour
prepend the ~ with a ^ , eg ^^~FG

